# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: actor-semantics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] In theoretical computer science, **Actor model theory** concerns theoretical issues for the Actor model.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] Actors are the primitives that form the basis of the Actor model of concurrent digital computation.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] In response to a message that it receives, an Actor can make local decisions, create more Actors, send more messages, and designate how to respond to the next message received.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] Actor model theory incorporates theories of the events and structures of Actor computations, their proof theory, and denotational models.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] From the definition of an Actor, it can be seen that numerous events take place: local decisions, creating Actors, sending messages, receiving messages, and designating how to respond to the next message received.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] However, this article focuses on just those events that are the arrival of a message sent to an Actor.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] This article reports on the results published in Hewitt [2006].
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] : There are at most countably many events.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] The activation ordering (`-≈→`) is a fundamental ordering that models one event activating another (there must be energy flow in the message passing from an event to an event which it activates).
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] The arrival ordering of an Actor `x` ( `-x→`) models the (total) ordering of events in which a message arrives at `x`.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] Arrival ordering is determined by *arbitration* in processing messages (often making use of a digital circuit called an arbiter).
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] The arrival events of an Actor are on its world line.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] The arrival ordering means that the Actor model inherently has indeterminacy (see Indeterminacy in concurrent computation).
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] The combined ordering (denoted by `→`) is defined to be the transitive closure of the activation ordering and the arrival orderings of all Actors.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] The combined ordering is obviously transitive by definition.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] , linearly ordered sets) of events between two events in the combined ordering →.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] It is sufficient to show that there is an Actor computation that satisfies the previously stated laws but violates the Law of Finite Chains Between Events in the Combined Ordering.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] Furthermore all of the laws stated before the Law of Strict Causality for the Combined Ordering are satisfied.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] However, we know from physics that infinite energy cannot be expended along a finite trajectory.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] Therefore, since the Actor model is based on physics, the Law of Finite Chains Between Events in the Combined Ordering was taken as an axiom of the Actor model.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] The law of discreteness rules out Zeno machines and is related to results on Petri nets [Best *et al.* 1984, 1987].
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] The Law of Discreteness implies the property of unbounded nondeterminism.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] The combined ordering is used by [Clinger 1981] in the construction of a denotational model of Actors (see denotational semantics).
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] Clinger [1981] used the Actor event model described above to construct a denotational model for Actors using power domains.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model-theory] Subsequently, Hewitt [2006] augmented the diagrams with arrival times to construct a technically simpler denotational model that is easier to understand.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] The **actor model** in computer science is a mathematical model of concurrent computation that treats an *actor* as the basic building block of concurrent computation.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] In response to a message it receives, an actor can: make local decisions, create more actors, send more messages, and determine how to respond to the next message received.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Actors may modify their own private state, but can only affect each other indirectly through messaging (removing the need for lock-based synchronization).
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] It has been used both as a framework for a theoretical understanding of computation and as the theoretical basis for several practical implementations of concurrent systems.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] The relationship of the model to other work is discussed in actor model and process calculi.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] According to Carl Hewitt, unlike previous models of computation, the actor model was inspired by physics, including general relativity and quantum mechanics.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] It was also influenced by the programming languages Lisp, Simula, early versions of Smalltalk, capability-based systems, and packet switching.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Following Hewitt, Bishop, and Steiger's 1973 publication, Irene Greif developed an operational semantics for the actor model as part of her doctoral research.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Two years later, Henry Baker and Hewitt published a set of axiomatic laws for actor systems.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Other major milestones include William Clinger's 1981 dissertation introducing a denotational semantics based on power domains and Gul Agha's 1985 dissertation which further developed a transition-based semantic model complementary to Clinger's.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] This resulted in the full development of actor model theory.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Research groups led by Chuck Seitz at California Institute of Technology (Caltech) and Bill Dally at MIT constructed computer architectures that further developed the message passing in the model.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] The actor model adopts the philosophy that *everything is an actor*.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] This is similar to the *everything is an object* philosophy used by some object-oriented programming languages.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] There is no assumed sequence to the above actions and they could be carried out in parallel.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Decoupling the sender from communications sent was a fundamental advance of the actor model enabling asynchronous communication and control structures as patterns of passing messages.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Recipients of messages are identified by address, sometimes called "mailing address".
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Thus an actor can only communicate with actors whose addresses it has.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] It can obtain those from a message it receives, or if the address is for an actor it has itself created.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] The actor model is characterized by inherent concurrency of computation within and among actors, dynamic creation of actors, inclusion of actor addresses in messages, and interaction only through direct asynchronous message passing with no restriction on message arrival order.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Over the years, several different formal systems have been developed which permit reasoning about systems in the actor model.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] The actor model can be used as a framework for modeling, understanding, and reasoning about a wide range of concurrent systems.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] The actor model is about the semantics of message passing.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Arguably, the first concurrent programs were interrupt handlers.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] During the course of its normal operation a computer needed to be able to receive information from outside (characters from a keyboard, packets from a network, *etc*).
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] So when the information arrived the execution of the computer was *interrupted* and special code (called an interrupt handler) was called to put the information in a data buffer where it could be subsequently retrieved.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] In the early 1960s, interrupts began to be used to simulate the concurrent execution of several programs on one processor.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Having concurrency with shared memory gave rise to the problem of concurrency control.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Originally, this problem was conceived as being one of mutual exclusion on a single computer.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Edsger Dijkstra developed semaphores and later, between 1971 and 1973, Tony Hoare and Per Brinch Hansen developed monitors to solve the mutual exclusion problem.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] However, neither of these solutions provided a programming language construct that encapsulated access to shared resources.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] This encapsulation was later accomplished by the serializer construct ([Hewitt and Atkinson 1977, 1979] and [Atkinson 1980]).
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Each computational step was from one global state of the computation to the next global state.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] The global state approach was continued in automata theory for finite-state machines and push down stack machines, including their nondeterministic versions.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Such nondeterministic automata have the property of bounded nondeterminism; that is, if a machine always halts when started in its initial state, then there is a bound on the number of states in which it halts.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Edsger Dijkstra further developed the nondeterministic global state approach.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Hewitt argued that the actor model should provide the guarantee of service.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] In Dijkstra's model, although there could be an unbounded amount of time between the execution of sequential instructions on a computer, a (parallel) program that started out in a well defined state could terminate in only a bounded number of states [Dijkstra 1976].
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Consequently, his model could not provide the guarantee of service.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Dijkstra argued that it was impossible to implement unbounded nondeterminism.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Hewitt argued otherwise: there is no bound that can be placed on how long it takes a computational circuit called an *arbiter* to settle (see metastability (electronics)).
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] The actor model features unbounded nondeterminism which was captured in a mathematical model by Will Clinger using domain theory.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] In the actor model, there is no global state.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Messages in the actor model are not necessarily buffered.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] This was a sharp break with previous approaches to models of concurrent computation.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] The lack of buffering caused a great deal of misunderstanding at the time of the development of the actor model and is still a controversial issue.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Some researchers argued that the messages are buffered in the "ether" or the "environment".
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Also, messages in the actor model are simply sent (like packets in IP); there is no requirement for a synchronous handshake with the recipient.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] A natural development of the actor model was to allow addresses in messages.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Influenced by packet switched networks [1961 and 1964], Hewitt proposed the development of a new model of concurrent computation in which communications would not have any required fields at all: they could be empty.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Of course, if the sender of a communication desired a recipient to have access to addresses which the recipient did not already have, the address would have to be sent in the communication.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] The original actor could accomplish this by sending a communication that includes the message it wishes to send, along with the address of the third actor that will handle the response.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] This third actor that will handle the response is called the *resumption* (sometimes also called a continuation or stack frame).
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] When the recipient actor is ready to send a response, it sends the response message to the *resumption* actor address that was included in the original communication.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] As opposed to the previous approach based on composing sequential processes, the actor model was developed as an inherently concurrent model.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] In the actor model sequentiality was a special case that derived from concurrent computation as explained in actor model theory.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Hewitt argued against adding the requirement that messages must arrive in the order in which they are sent to the actor.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] If output message ordering is desired, then it can be modeled by a queue actor that provides this functionality.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Such a queue actor would queue the messages that arrived so that they could be retrieved in FIFO order.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] So if an actor `X` sent a message `M1` to an actor `Y`, and later `X` sent another message `M2` to `Y`, there is no requirement that `M1` arrives at `Y` before `M2`.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] In this respect the actor model mirrors packet switching systems which do not guarantee that packets must be received in the order sent.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Not providing the order of delivery guarantee allows packet switching to buffer packets, use multiple paths to send packets, resend damaged packets, and to provide other optimizations.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] For more example, actors are allowed to pipeline the processing of messages.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] What this means is that in the course of processing a message `M1`, an actor can designate the behavior to be used to process the next message, and then in fact begin processing another message `M2` before it has finished processing `M1`.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Just because an actor is allowed to pipeline the processing of messages does not mean that it *must* pipeline the processing.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Whether a message is pipelined is an engineering tradeoff.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] How would an external observer know whether the processing of a message by an actor has been pipelined?
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] There is no ambiguity in the definition of an actor created by the possibility of pipelining.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Of course, it is possible to perform the pipeline optimization incorrectly in some implementations, in which case unexpected behavior may occur.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Another important characteristic of the actor model is locality.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Locality means that in processing a message, an actor can send messages only to addresses that it receives in the message, addresses that it already had before it received the message, and addresses for actors that it creates while processing the message.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Also locality means that there is no simultaneous change in multiple locations.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] In this way it differs from some other models of concurrency, *e.g.*, the Petri net model in which tokens are simultaneously removed from multiple locations and placed in other locations.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] The idea of composing actor systems into larger ones is an important aspect of modularity that was developed in Gul Agha's doctoral dissertation, developed later by Gul Agha, Ian Mason, Scott Smith, and Carolyn Talcott.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] A key innovation was the introduction of *behavior* specified as a mathematical function to express what an actor does when it processes a message, including specifying a new behavior to process the next message that arrives.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Behaviors provided a mechanism to mathematically model the sharing in concurrency.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Behaviors also freed the actor model from implementation details, *e.g.*, the Smalltalk-72 token stream interpreter.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] However, the efficient implementation of systems described by the actor model require *extensive* optimization.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] See Actor model implementation for details.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Other concurrency systems (*e.g.*, process calculi) can be modeled in the actor model using a two-phase commit protocol.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] There is a *Computational Representation Theorem* in the actor model for systems which are closed in the sense that they do not receive communications from outside.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] In this way, ${\mathtt {S}}$ can be mathematically characterized in terms of all its possible behaviors (including those involving unbounded nondeterminism).
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] A consequence of the above theorem is that a finite actor can nondeterministically respond with an uncountable number of different outputs.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] One of the key motivations for the development of the actor model was to understand and deal with the control structure issues that arose in development of the Planner programming language.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Once the actor model was initially defined, an important challenge was to understand the power of the model relative to Robert Kowalski's thesis that "computation can be subsumed by deduction".
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Hewitt argued that Kowalski's thesis turned out to be false for the concurrent computation in the actor model (see Indeterminacy in concurrent computation).
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Nevertheless, attempts were made to extend logic programming to concurrent computation.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] However, Hewitt and Agha [1991] claimed that the resulting systems were not deductive in the following sense: computational steps of the concurrent logic programming systems do not follow deductively from previous steps (see Indeterminacy in concurrent computation).
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Recently, logic programming has been integrated into the actor model in a way that maintains logical semantics.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Migration in the actor model is the ability of actors to change locations.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] *E.g.*, in his dissertation, Aki Yonezawa modeled a post office that customer actors could enter, change locations within while operating, and exit.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] An actor that can migrate can be modeled by having a location actor that changes when the actor migrates.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] However the faithfulness of this modeling is controversial and the subject of research.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] A delicate point in the actor model is the ability to synthesize the address of an actor.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] In some cases security can be used to prevent the synthesis of addresses (see Security).
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] However, if an actor address is simply a bit string then clearly it can be synthesized although it may be difficult or even infeasible to guess the address of an actor if the bit strings are long enough.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] SOAP uses a URL for the address of an endpoint where an actor can be reached.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Since a URL is a character string, it can clearly be synthesized although encryption can make it virtually impossible to guess.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Synthesizing the addresses of actors is usually modeled using mapping.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] The idea is to use an actor system to perform the mapping to the actual actor addresses.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] For example, on a computer the memory structure of the computer can be modeled as an actor system that does the mapping.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] In the case of SOAP addresses, it's modeling the DNS and the rest of the URL mapping.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Robin Milner's initial published work on concurrency was also notable in that it was not based on composing sequential processes.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] His work differed from the actor model because it was based on a fixed number of processes of fixed topology communicating numbers and strings using synchronous communication.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Later versions of CSP abandoned communication based on process names in favor of anonymous communication via channels, an approach also used in Milner's work on the calculus of communicating systems (CCS) and the π-calculus.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] These early models by Milner and Hoare both had the property of bounded nondeterminism.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Modern, theoretical CSP ([Hoare 1985] and [Roscoe 2005]) explicitly provides unbounded nondeterminism.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] The actor model has been influential on both theory development and practical software development.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] The actor model has influenced the development of the π-calculus and subsequent process calculi.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] The actor model has had extensive influence on commercial practice.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] For example, Twitter has used actors for scalability.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Also, Microsoft has used the actor model in the development of its Asynchronous Agents Library.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] There are multiple other actor libraries listed in the actor libraries and frameworks section below.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Many of the ideas introduced in the actor model are now also finding application in multi-agent systems for these same reasons [Hewitt 2006b 2007b].
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] The key difference is that agent systems (in most definitions) impose extra constraints upon the actors, typically requiring that they make use of commitments and goals.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] A number of different programming languages employ the actor model or some variation of it.
[src:actor-semantics/actor-model] Actor libraries or frameworks have also been implemented to permit actor-style programming in languages that don't have actors built-in.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] Hewitt obtained his PhD in mathematics at MIT in 1971, under the supervision of Seymour Papert, Marvin Minsky, and Mike Paterson.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] He began his employment at MIT that year, and retired from the faculty of the MIT Department of Electrical Engineering and Computer Science during the 1999–2000 school year.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] He became emeritus in the department in 2000.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] Among the doctoral students that Hewitt supervised during his time at MIT are Gul Agha, Henry Baker, William Clinger, Irene Greif, and Akinori Yonezawa.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] From September 1989 to August 1990, Hewitt was the IBM Chair Visiting professor in the Department of Computer Science at Keio University in Japan.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] He has also been a visiting professor at Stanford University.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] Hewitt was best known for his work on the actor model of computation.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] For the last decade, his work had been in "inconsistency robustness", which aims to provide practical rigorous foundations for systems dealing with pervasively inconsistent information.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] This work grew out of his doctoral dissertation focused on the procedural (as opposed to logical) embedding of knowledge, which was embodied in the Planner programming language.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] His publications also include contributions in the areas of open information systems, organizational and multi-agent systems, logic programming, concurrent programming, paraconsistent logic and cloud computing.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] The Planner language was developed during the late 1960s as part of Hewitt's doctoral research in MIT's Artificial Intelligence Laboratory.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] Hewitt's work on Planner introduced the notion of the "procedural embedding of knowledge", which was an alternative to the logical approach to knowledge encoding for artificial intelligence pioneered by John McCarthy.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] Planner has been described as "extremely ambitious".
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] A subset of Planner called Micro-Planner was implemented at MIT by Gerry Sussman, Drew McDermott, Eugene Charniak and Terry Winograd and was used in Winograd's SHRDLU program, Charniak's natural language story understanding work, and L.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] Thorne McCarty's work on legal reasoning.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] Planner was almost completely implemented in Popler by Julian Davies at Edinburgh.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] Planner also influenced the later development of other AI research languages such as Muddle and Conniver, as well as the Smalltalk object-oriented programming language.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] Hewitt's own work on Planner continued with Muddle (later called MDL), which was developed in the early 1970s by Sussman, Hewitt, Chris Reeve, and David Cressey as a stepping-stone towards a full implementation of Planner.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] Muddle was implemented as an extended version of Lisp, and introduced several features that were later adopted by Conniver, Lisp Machine Lisp, and Common Lisp.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] However, in late 1972 Hewitt abruptly halted his development of the Planner design in his thesis, when he and his graduate students invented the actor model of computation.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] Hewitt's work on the actor model of computation spanned over 30 years, beginning with the introduction of the model in a 1973 paper authored by Hewitt, Peter Bishop, and Richard Steiger, and including new results on actor model semantics published as recently as 2006.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] Much of this work was carried out in collaboration with students in Hewitt's Message Passing Semantics Group at MIT's Artificial Intelligence Lab.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] Sussman and Steele developed the Scheme programming language in an effort to gain a better understanding of the actor model.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] They discovered that their operator to create an actor, ALPHA, and their operator to create a function, LAMBDA, were identical, so they only kept LAMBDA for both.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] A number of other programming languages were developed to specifically implement the actor model, such as ACT-1, SALSA, Caltrop, E and ActorScript.
[src:actor-semantics/carl-hewitt] The actor model also influenced the development of the π-calculus.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] The Erlang programming language has data, pattern matching, and functional programming.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] The sequential subset of the Erlang language supports eager evaluation, single assignment, and dynamic typing.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] A normal Erlang application is built out of hundreds of small Erlang processes.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] It was originally proprietary software within Ericsson, developed by Joe Armstrong, Robert Virding, and Mike Williams in 1986, but was released as free and open-source software in 1998.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Erlang/OTP is supported and maintained by the Open Telecom Platform (OTP) product unit at Ericsson.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] The name *Erlang*, attributed to Bjarne Däcker, has been presumed by those working on the telephony switches (for whom the language was designed) to be a reference to Danish mathematician and engineer Agner Krarup Erlang and a syllabic abbreviation of "Ericsson Language".
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Erlang was designed with the aim of improving the development of telephony applications.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] The initial version of Erlang was implemented in Prolog and was influenced by the programming language PLEX used in earlier Ericsson exchanges.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] By 1988 Erlang had proven that it was suitable for prototyping telephone exchanges, but the Prolog interpreter was far too slow.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] One group within Ericsson estimated that it would need to be 40 times faster to be suitable for production use.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] In 1992, work began on the BEAM virtual machine (VM), which compiles Erlang to C using a mix of natively compiled code and threaded code to strike a balance between performance and disk space.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] According to co-inventor Joe Armstrong, the language went from laboratory product to real applications following the collapse of the next-generation AXE telephone exchange named *AXE-N* in 1995.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] As a result, Erlang was chosen for the next Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) exchange *AXD*.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] In February 1998, Ericsson Radio Systems banned the in-house use of Erlang for new products, citing a preference for non-proprietary languages.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] The ban caused Armstrong and others to make plans to leave Ericsson.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] In March 1998 Ericsson announced the AXD301 switch, containing over a million lines of Erlang and reported to achieve a high availability of nine "9"s.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] In December 1998, the implementation of Erlang was open-sourced and most of the Erlang team resigned to form a new company, Bluetail AB.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Ericsson eventually relaxed the ban and re-hired Armstrong in 2004.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] In 2006, native symmetric multiprocessing support was added to the runtime system and VM.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Erlang applications are built of very lightweight Erlang processes in the Erlang runtime system.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] The Erlang runtime system provides strict process isolation between Erlang processes (this includes data and garbage collection, separated individually by each Erlang process) and transparent communication between processes (see Location transparency) on different Erlang nodes (on different hosts).
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] In 2014, Ericsson reported Erlang was being used in its support nodes, and in GPRS, 3G and LTE mobile networks worldwide and also by Nortel and Deutsche Telekom.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Erlang is the programming language used to code WhatsApp.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] It is also the language of choice for Ejabberd – an XMPP messaging server.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Elixir is a programming language that compiles into BEAM byte code (via Erlang Abstract Format).
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Since being released as open source, Erlang has been spreading beyond telecoms, establishing itself in other vertical markets such as FinTech, gaming, healthcare, automotive, Internet of Things and blockchain.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Apart from WhatsApp, there are other companies listed as Erlang's success stories, including Vocalink (a MasterCard company), Goldman Sachs, Nintendo, AdRoll, Grindr, BT Mobile, Samsung, OpenX, and SITA.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Omitting the comments gives a much shorter program.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] The above example recursively invokes the function `qsort` until nothing remains to be sorted.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] The expression `[Front || Front <- Rest, Front < Pivot]` is a list comprehension, meaning "Construct a list of elements `Front` such that `Front` is a member of `Rest`, and `Front` is less than `Pivot`." `++` is the list concatenation operator.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] A comparison function can be used for more complicated structures for the sake of readability.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] A `Pivot` is taken from the first parameter given to `qsort()` and the rest of `Lists` is named `Rest`.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] The anonymous function is named `Smaller` in the parameter list of the second definition of `qsort` so that it can be referenced by that name within that function.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] It is not named in the first definition of `qsort`, which deals with the base case of an empty list and thus has no need of this function, let alone a name for it.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Integers are written as sequences of decimal digits, for example, 12, 12375 and -23427 are integers.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Integer arithmetic is exact and only limited by available memory on the machine.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Atoms are used within a program to denote distinguished values.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] They are written as strings of consecutive alphanumeric characters, the first character being lowercase.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Atoms can contain any character if they are enclosed within single quotes and an escape convention exists which allows any character to be used within an atom.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Atoms are never garbage collected and should be used with caution, especially if using dynamic atom generation.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] References are globally unique symbols whose only property is that they can be compared for equality.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Binaries provide a space-efficient way of storing binary data.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Erlang primitives exist for composing and decomposing binaries and for efficient input/output of binaries.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Pids are references to Erlang processes.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Ports are used to communicate with the external world.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Tuples are containers for a fixed number of Erlang data types.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] The arguments can be primitive data types or compound data types.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Any element of a tuple can be accessed in constant time.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Lists are containers for a variable number of Erlang data types.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] The first element of a list can be accessed in constant time.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Maps contain a variable number of key-value associations.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Strings are written as doubly quoted lists of characters.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] code points for the characters in the string.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Records provide a convenient way for associating a tag with each of the elements in a tuple.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] This allows one to refer to an element of a tuple by name and not by position.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] A pre-compiler takes the record definition and replaces it with the appropriate tuple reference.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Erlang is designed with a mechanism that makes it easy for external processes to monitor for crashes (or hardware failures), rather than an in-process mechanism like exception handling used in many other programming languages.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Crashes are reported like other messages, which is the only way processes can communicate with each other, and subprocesses can be spawned cheaply (see below).
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] The "let it crash" philosophy prefers that a process be completely restarted rather than trying to recover from a serious failure.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Though it still requires handling of errors, this philosophy results in less code devoted to defensive programming where error-handling code is highly contextual and specific.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] A typical Erlang application is written in the form of a supervisor tree.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] This architecture is based on a hierarchy of processes in which the top level process is known as a "supervisor".
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] The supervisor then spawns multiple child processes that act either as workers or more, lower level supervisors.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Such hierarchies can exist to arbitrary depths and have proven to provide a highly scalable and fault-tolerant environment within which application functionality can be implemented.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Within a supervisor tree, all supervisor processes are responsible for managing the lifecycle of their child processes, and this includes handling situations in which those child processes crash.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Any process can become a supervisor by first spawning a child process, then calling `erlang:monitor/2` on that process.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] If the monitored process then crashes, the supervisor will receive a message containing a tuple whose first member is the atom `'DOWN'`.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] The supervisor is responsible firstly for listening for such messages and for taking the appropriate action to correct the error condition.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Erlang's main strength is support for concurrency.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] It has a small but powerful set of primitives to create processes and communicate among them.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Erlang is conceptually similar to the language occam, though it recasts the ideas of communicating sequential processes (CSP) in a functional framework and uses asynchronous message passing.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Processes are the primary means to structure an Erlang application.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] They are neither operating system processes nor threads, but lightweight processes that are scheduled by BEAM.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Like operating system processes (but unlike operating system threads), they share no state with each other.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] The estimated minimal overhead for each is 300 words.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Thus, many processes can be created without degrading performance.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] In 2005, a benchmark with 20 million processes was successfully performed with 64-bit Erlang on a machine with 16 GB random-access memory (RAM; total 800 bytes/process).
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Erlang has supported symmetric multiprocessing since release R11B of May 2006.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] While threads need external library support in most languages, Erlang provides language-level features to create and manage processes with the goal of simplifying concurrent programming.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Though all concurrency is explicit in Erlang, processes communicate using message passing instead of shared variables, which removes the need for explicit locks (a locking scheme is still used internally by the VM).
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Inter-process communication works via a shared-nothing asynchronous message passing system: every process has a "mailbox", a queue of messages that have been sent by other processes and not yet consumed.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] A process uses the `receive` primitive to retrieve messages that match desired patterns.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] A message-handling routine tests messages in turn against each pattern, until one of them matches.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] When the message is consumed and removed from the mailbox the process resumes execution.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] A message may comprise any Erlang structure, including primitives (integers, floats, characters, atoms), tuples, lists, and functions.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] As the example shows, processes may be created on remote nodes, and communication with them is transparent in the sense that communication with remote processes works exactly as communication with local processes.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Concurrency supports the primary method of error-handling in Erlang.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] When a process crashes, it neatly exits and sends a message to the controlling process which can then take action, such as starting a new process that takes over the old process's task.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] The official reference implementation of Erlang uses BEAM.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] BEAM is included in the official distribution of Erlang, called Erlang/OTP.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] BEAM executes bytecode which is converted to threaded code at load time.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] It also includes a native code compiler on most platforms, developed by the High Performance Erlang Project (HiPE) at Uppsala University.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Since October 2001 the HiPE system is fully integrated in Ericsson's Open Source Erlang/OTP system.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] It also supports interpreting, directly from source code via abstract syntax tree, via script as of R11B-5 release of Erlang.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Erlang supports language-level Dynamic Software Updating.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] To implement this, code is loaded and managed as "module" units; the module is a compilation unit.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] The system can keep two versions of a module in memory at the same time, and processes can concurrently run code from each.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] The versions are referred to as the "new" and the "old" version.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] A process will not move into the new version until it makes an external call to its module.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] For the second version, we add the possibility to reset the count to zero.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Only when receiving a message consisting of the atom `code_switch` will the loop execute an external call to codeswitch/1 (`?MODULE` is a preprocessor macro for the current module).
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] If there is a new version of the *counter* module in memory, then its codeswitch/1 function will be called.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] The practice of having a specific entry-point into a new version allows the programmer to transform state to what is needed in the newer version.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] In the example, the state is kept as an integer.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] In practice, systems are built up using design principles from the Open Telecom Platform, which leads to more code upgradable designs.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Successful hot code loading is exacting.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Code must be written with care to make use of Erlang's facilities.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] In 1998, Ericsson released Erlang as free and open-source software to ensure its independence from a single vendor and to increase awareness of the language.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Erlang, together with libraries and the real-time distributed database Mnesia, forms the OTP collection of libraries.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Ericsson and a few other companies support Erlang commercially.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Since the open source release, Erlang has been used by several firms worldwide, including Nortel and Deutsche Telekom.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Although Erlang was designed to fill a niche and has remained an obscure language for most of its existence, its popularity is growing due to demand for concurrent services.
[src:actor-semantics/erlang-programming-language] Erlang has found some use in fielding massively multiplayer online role-playing game (MMORPG) servers.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] In computer science, the Actor model, first published in 1973, is a mathematical model of concurrent computation.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] A fundamental challenge in defining the Actor model is that it did not provide for global states so that a computational step could not be defined as going from one global state to the next global state as had been done in all previous models of computation.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] In 1963 in the field of Artificial Intelligence, John McCarthy introduced situation variables in logic in the Situational Calculus.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] In McCarthy and Hayes 1969, a situation is defined as "the complete state of the universe at an instant of time." In this respect, the situations of McCarthy are not suitable for use in the Actor model since it has no global states.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Partial orderings on such events have been axiomatized in the Actor model and their relationship to physics explored (see Actor model theory).
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] According to Hewitt (2006), the Actor model is based on physics in contrast with other models of computation that were based on mathematical logic, set theory, algebra, *etc.* Physics influenced the Actor model in many ways, especially quantum physics and relativistic physics.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] One issue is what can be observed about Actor systems.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] The question does not have an obvious answer because it poses both theoretical and observational challenges similar to those that had arisen in constructing the foundations of quantum physics.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] In concrete terms for Actor systems, typically we cannot observe the details by which the arrival order of messages for an Actor is determined (see Indeterminacy in concurrent computation).
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Attempting to do so affects the results and can even push the indeterminacy elsewhere.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] *e.g.*, see metastability in electronics.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Instead of observing the insides of arbitration processes of Actor computations, we await the outcomes.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] The Actor model builds on previous models of computation.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] The lambda calculus of Alonzo Church can be viewed as the earliest message passing programming language (see Hewitt, Bishop, and Steiger 1973; Abelson and Sussman 1985).
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] For example, the lambda expression below implements a tree data structure when supplied with parameters for a leftSubTree and rightSubTree.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] When such a tree is given a parameter message "getLeft", it returns leftSubTree and likewise when given the message "getRight" it returns rightSubTree.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] However, the semantics of the lambda calculus were expressed using variable substitution in which the values of parameters were substituted into the body of an invoked lambda expression.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] The substitution model is unsuitable for concurrency because it does not allow the capability of sharing of changing resources.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Inspired by the lambda calculus, the interpreter for the programming language Lisp made use of a data structure called an environment so that the values of parameters did not have to be substituted into the body of an invoked lambda expression.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] This allowed for sharing of the effects of updating shared data structures but did not provide for concurrency.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Simula 67 pioneered using message passing for computation, motivated by discrete event simulation applications.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] These applications had become large and unmodular in previous simulation languages.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] At each time step, a large central program would have to go through and update the state of each simulation object that changed depending on the state of whichever simulation objects it interacted with on that step.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Kristen Nygaard and Ole-Johan Dahl developed the idea (first described in an IFIP workshop in 1967) of having methods on each object that would update its own local state based on messages from other objects.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] In addition they introduced a class structure for objects with inheritance.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Their innovations considerably improved the modularity of programs.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] However, Simula used coroutine control structure instead of true concurrency.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Alan Kay was influenced by message passing in the pattern-directed invocation of Planner in developing Smalltalk-71.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] In 1972 Kay visited MIT and discussed some of his ideas for Smalltalk-72 building on the Logo work of Seymour Papert and the "little person" model of computation used for teaching children to program.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] However, the message passing of Smalltalk-72 was quite complex.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Code in the language was viewed by the interpreter as simply a stream of tokens.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] The first (token) encountered (in a program) was looked up in the dynamic context, to determine the receiver of the subsequent message.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] The name lookup began with the class dictionary of the current activation.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Failing there, it moved to the sender of that activation and so on up the sender chain.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] When a binding was finally found for the token, its value became the receiver of a new message, and the interpreter activated the code for that object's class.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Thus the message-passing model in Smalltalk-72 was closely tied to a particular machine model and programming-language syntax that did not lend itself to concurrency.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Also, although the system was bootstrapped on itself, the language constructs were not formally defined as objects that respond to **Eval** messages (see discussion below).
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] This led some to believe that a new mathematical model of concurrent computation based on message passing should be simpler than Smalltalk-72.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Subsequent versions of the Smalltalk language largely followed the path of using the virtual methods of Simula in the message-passing structure of programs.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] However Smalltalk-72 made primitives such as integers, floating point numbers, *etc.* into objects.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] The authors of Simula had considered making such primitives into objects but refrained largely for efficiency reasons.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] The Smalltalk system went on to become very influential, innovating in bitmap displays, personal computing, the class browser interface, and many other ways.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] For details see Kay's *The Early History of Smalltalk*.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Meanwhile, the Actor efforts at MIT remained focused on developing the science and engineering of higher level concurrency.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Prior to the development of the Actor model, Petri nets were widely used to model nondeterministic computation.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] However, they were widely acknowledged to have an important limitation: they modeled control flow but not data flow.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Consequently, they were not readily composable, thereby limiting their modularity.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Hewitt pointed out another difficulty with Petri nets: simultaneous action.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] *I.e.*, the atomic step of computation in Petri nets is a transition in which tokens *simultaneously* disappear from the input places of a transition and appear in the output places.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] The physical basis of using a primitive with this kind of simultaneity seemed questionable to him.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Despite these apparent difficulties, Petri nets continue to be a popular approach to modelling concurrency, and are still the subject of active research.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Prior to the Actor model, concurrency was defined in low-level machine terms of threads, locks and buffers(channels).
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] It certainly is the case that implementations of the Actor model typically make use of these hardware capabilities.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] However, there is no reason that the model could not be implemented directly in hardware without exposing any hardware threads and locks.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Also, there is no necessary relationship between the number of Actors, threads, and locks that might be involved in a computation.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Implementations of the Actor model are free to make use of threads and locks in any way that is compatible with the laws for Actors.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] An important challenge in defining the Actor model was to abstract away implementation details.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] For example, consider the following question: "Does each Actor have a queue in which its communications are stored until received by the Actor to be processed?" Carl Hewitt argued against including such queues as an integral part of the Actor model.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] One consideration was that such queues could themselves be modeled as Actors that received messages to enqueue and dequeue the communications.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Another consideration was that some Actors would not use such queues in their actual implementation.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] *E.g.,* an Actor might have a network of arbiters instead.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Of course, there is a mathematical abstraction which is the *sequence* of communications that have been received by an Actor.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] But this sequence emerged only as the Actor operated.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] In fact the ordering of this sequence can be indeterminate (see Indeterminacy in concurrent computation).
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Another example of abstracting away implementation detail was the question of interpretation: "Should interpretation be an integral part of the Actor model?" The idea of interpretation is that an Actor would be defined by how its program script processed eval messages.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] (In this way Actors would be defined in a manner analogous to Lisp which was "defined" by a meta-circular interpreter procedure named eval written in Lisp.) Hewitt argued against making interpretation integral to the Actor model.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] One consideration was that to process the eval messages, the program script of an Actor would itself have a program script (which in turn would have ...)!
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Another consideration was that some Actors would not use interpretation in their actual interpretation.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] *E.g.,* an Actor might be implemented in hardware instead.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Of course there is nothing wrong with interpretation *per se*.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Also implementing interpreters using eval messages is more modular and extensible than the monolithic interpreter approach of Lisp.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Nevertheless, progress developing the model was steady.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] In 1975, Irene Greif published the first operational model in her dissertation.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] On the other hand, the Actor model is capable of expressing all of the parallelism in the lambda calculus.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Two years after Greif published her operational model, Carl Hewitt and Henry Baker published the Laws for Actors.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Using the laws of the Actor model, Hewitt and Baker proved that any Actor that behaves like a function is continuous in the sense defined by Dana Scott (see denotational semantics).
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Aki Yonezawa published his specification and verification techniques for Actors.
[src:actor-semantics/history-of-the-actor-model] Russ Atkinson and Carl Hewitt published a paper on specification and proof techniques for serializers providing an efficient solution to encapsulating shared resources for concurrency control.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] In computer science, **message passing** is a technique for invoking behavior (i.e., running a program) on a computer.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] The invoking program sends a message to a process (which may be an actor or object) and relies on that process and its supporting infrastructure to then select and run some appropriate code.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Message passing differs from conventional programming where a process, subroutine, or function is directly invoked by name.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Message passing is key to some models of concurrency and object-oriented programming.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Message passing is ubiquitous in modern computer software.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] It is used as a way for the objects that make up a program to work with each other and as a means for objects and systems running on different computers (e.g., the Internet) to interact.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Message passing may be implemented by various mechanisms, including channels.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Message passing is a technique for invoking behavior (i.e., running a program) on a computer.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] In contrast to the traditional technique of calling a program by name, message passing uses an object model to distinguish the general function from the specific implementations.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] The invoking program sends a message and relies on the object to select and execute the appropriate code.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] The justifications for using an intermediate layer essentially falls into two categories: encapsulation and distribution.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Message passing is a core technique used for communication between processes, threads, objects, or nodes in both concurrent and distributed systems.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] It enables software components to exchange information without sharing memory, often using communication channels, buffers, or middleware to transport messages between senders and receivers.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] In some models, message passing can be implemented synchronously, where the sender waits for a reply, or asynchronously, where messages are queued for later processing.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Encapsulation is the idea that software objects should be able to invoke services on other objects without knowing or caring about how those services are implemented.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Encapsulation can reduce the amount of coding logic and make systems more maintainable.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] E.g., rather than having IF-THEN statements that determine which subroutine or function to call, a developer can just send a message to the object and the object will select the appropriate code based on its type.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] One of the first examples of how this can be used was in the domain of computer graphics.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] There are various complexities involved in manipulating graphic objects.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] For example, simply using the right formula to compute the area of an enclosed shape will vary depending on if the shape is a triangle, rectangle, ellipse, or circle.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] In traditional computer programming, this would result in long IF-THEN statements testing what sort of object the shape was and calling the appropriate code.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] The object-oriented way to handle this is to define a class called `Shape` with subclasses such as `Rectangle` and `Ellipse` (which, in turn, have subclasses `Square` and `Circle`) and then to simply send a message to any `Shape` asking it to compute its area.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Each `Shape` object will then invoke the subclass's method with the formula appropriate for that kind of object.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Distributed message passing provides developers with a layer of the architecture that provides common services to build systems made up of sub-systems that run on disparate computers in different locations and at different times.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Synchronous message passing occurs between objects that are running at the same time.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] It is used by object-oriented programming languages such as Java and Smalltalk.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Synchronous messaging is analogous to a synchronous function call; just as the function caller waits until the function completes, the sending process waits until the receiving process accepts the message.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] This can make synchronous communication unworkable for some applications.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] For example, large, distributed systems may not perform well enough to be usable.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Such large, distributed systems may need to operate while some of their subsystems are down for maintenance, etc.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Imagine a busy business office having 100 desktop computers that send emails to each other using synchronous message passing exclusively.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] One worker turning off their computer can cause the other 99 computers to freeze until the worker turns their computer back on to process a single email.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Message passing systems can be broadly categorized based on how send and receive operations interact with executing processes.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] In **synchronous** message passing, the sending process may block until the receiver has accepted the message, ensuring tight coordination.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] In **asynchronous** models, the sender continues execution after sending a message, and messages are typically stored in a queue or buffer until the receiving process retrieves them.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] With asynchronous message passing the receiving object can be down or busy when the requesting object sends the message.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Continuing the function call analogy, it is like a function call that returns immediately, without waiting for the called function to complete.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Messages are sent to a queue where they are stored until the receiving process requests them.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] The receiving process processes its messages and sends results to a queue for pickup by the original process (or some designated next process).
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Asynchronous messaging requires additional capabilities for storing and retransmitting data for systems that may not run concurrently, and are generally handled by an intermediary level of software (often called middleware); a common type being Message-oriented middleware (MOM).
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] The buffer required in asynchronous communication can cause problems when it is full.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] A decision has to be made whether to block the sender or whether to discard future messages.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] If messages are dropped, communication is no longer reliable.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Synchronous communication can be built on top of asynchronous communication by using a Synchronizer.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] For example, the α-Synchronizer works by ensuring that the sender always waits for an acknowledgement message from the receiver.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] The sender only sends the next message after the acknowledgement has been received.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] On the other hand, asynchronous communication can also be built on top of synchronous communication.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] For example, modern microkernels generally only provide a synchronous messaging primitive and asynchronous messaging can be implemented on top by using helper threads.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Message-passing systems use either distributed or local objects.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] With distributed objects the sender and receiver may be on different computers, running different operating systems, using different programming languages, etc.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] In this case the bus layer takes care of details about converting data from one system to another, sending and receiving data across the network, etc.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] The Remote Procedure Call (RPC) protocol in Unix was an early example of this.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] With this type of message passing it is not a requirement that sender nor receiver use object-oriented programming.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Procedural language systems can be wrapped and treated as large grained objects capable of sending and receiving messages.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Examples of systems that support distributed objects are: Emerald, ONC RPC, CORBA, Java RMI, DCOM, SOAP, .NET Remoting, CTOS, QNX Neutrino RTOS, OpenBinder and D-Bus.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Distributed object systems have been called "shared nothing" systems because the message passing abstraction hides underlying state changes that may be used in the implementation of sending messages.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Distributed, or asynchronous, message-passing has additional overhead compared to calling a procedure.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] In message-passing, arguments must be copied to the new message.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Some arguments can contain megabytes of data, all of which must be copied and transmitted to the receiving object.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Traditional procedure calls differ from message-passing in terms of memory usage, transfer time and locality.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Arguments are passed to the receiver typically by general-purpose registers requiring no additional storage nor transfer time, or in a parameter list containing the arguments' addresses (a few bits).
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Address-passing is not possible for distributed systems since the systems use separate address spaces.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Web browsers and web servers are examples of processes that communicate by message-passing.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] A URL is an example of referencing a resource without exposing process internals.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] A subroutine call or method invocation will not exit until the invoked computation has terminated.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Asynchronous message-passing, by contrast, can result in a response arriving a significant time after the request message was sent.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] A message-handler will, in general, process messages from more than one sender.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] This means its state can change for reasons unrelated to the behavior of a single sender or client process.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] This is in contrast to the typical behavior of an object upon which methods are being invoked: the latter is expected to remain in the same state between method invocations.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] In other words, the message-handler behaves analogously to a volatile object.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] The prominent mathematical models of message passing are the Actor model and Pi calculus.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] In mathematical terms a message is the single means to pass control to an object.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] If the object responds to the message, it has a method for that message.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] Alan Kay has argued that message passing is more important than objects in OOP, and that objects themselves are often over-emphasized.
[src:actor-semantics/message-passing] The live distributed objects programming model builds upon this observation; it uses the concept of a distributed data flow to characterize the behavior of a complex distributed system in terms of message patterns, using high-level, functional-style specifications.
